"'''Recept'''" (pronounced {{IPAc-en|ˈ|r|iː|ˌ|s|ɛ|p|t}}) is a term used in the work of 19th-century [[Psychology|psychologist]] [[George Romanes]] to refer to an idea that is formed by the repetition of [[percept]]s (i.e., successive percepts of the same object).<ref>{{cite book |title=Webster's New International Dictionary |year=1913 |publisher=G. & C. Merriam |location=Springfield, Massachusetts |page=1781}} "A mental image or idea formed by successive percepts of the same or like objects, and thus accentuating their common characters; a generic image."</ref> The idea is similar to that of concatenated impressions, as seen in the work of [[David Hume]].
The term is used in [[Richard Maurice Bucke]]'s book, ''Cosmic Consciousness: A Study in the Evolution of the Human Mind''. Bucke was a 19th-century [[Canada|Canadian]] [[Psychiatry|psychiatrist]].
